EDA Task by Jaan Norit

Description of the data set

The enclosed data file contains real customer data from a retail bank, collected from May 2008 to June 2013. The bank had a goal to sell a product. In this case it was a term deposit. The marketing campaigns were based on phone calls. Often, more than one contact to the same customer was required in order to assess if the targeted product is subscribed to by a customer, which is indicated by 'yes' or 'no' to subscribe to a deposit.

The first step in the EDA of the data set will be the running of the R function str() on “my” data set. This displays the structure of the data. There are variables concerning Customer Attributes, Attributes of the Last Contact of the Current Campaign, Other Attributes and Social and Economic Context Attributes. Each variable will be part of an univariate analysis and plots section, which will be covered in the following.

Creation of a new variable

I created a new variable 'duration_in_minutes'. But it was not possible to create a plot with the new assigned vaiable. So I used duration in seconds. The duration distribution is heavily left skewed and the variance is relatively high. Moreover I hold the view that the duration is strong correlated with the succes rate. The longer the call, the more likely it is that a customer could be influenced to invest in a term deposit. The peak of the distribution is at 60 seconds. Thus I think that most call activities were not succeful. This thing should be looked deeper in further investigation. For example through plotting duration versus the succesrate of the call.

Passed_Days is the number of days that passed by after the customer was last contacted from a previous campaign. Since the variable 'Passed_Days' is very unevenly distributed I decided to transform it with the logarithm. The most frequent point was at 999 days. That seems strange. I think that this could be manually set to 999 if passed days were for example more than 100 or whatever.

In the graph, the distribution of the low days can not clearly be seen. Thus I decided to zoom in on that.

In this low days passed area the variance is pretty high. But on the whole the counts of all them aggregated are relatively small compared to the very high number of 999 days passed. This is a characteristic of the data set which has to be kept in mind if setting up a predictive model. One could take all of the low days passed data points in one bucket and could create a dummy variable which takes the value 1 if a low number of days passed or 0 for the 999 days passed. Nevertheless one will underestimate the effect of low days passed compared to 999 days passed, since the counts are very uneven distributed.

Bivariate Plots Section concerning customer attributes

The bivariate segments will always cover both, the Plots and Analysis section without making a new header accounting for the Analysis part. In this section I will look at the variables in relationship to the target variable subscription which is yes or no.

The plot shows that there is no really a difference in variance. Thus Age seems not to be a driver for succes. Further one can basically see that there are many more entries in the “no” bin. This is shown by the massive overplotting on the left bin. Both bins show that there is an age range, where most entries lie in. But this range is similar in both bins, indicating that there is no specific systematic difference in the age variable. This observation is confirmed as well in the box plots. Just the upper quartile of the “yes” boxplot exceeds the corresponding quartile in th 'no' boxplot. But I hold the view that this is just because of the smaller sample size and not due to systematic difference in the variables.

Further I run the ggpairs function on the variables Age and Subscription. Since the boxplot for subscription==yes look similar to the boxplot where subscription==no, I hold the view that there is no significant relationship between Age and the Subscription variable.

The Job distribution shows that “admin” and “blue collar” and the “technician” job are most likely to lead to a subscription. But as mentioned in the previous section, there are generally the most people with those three jobs. An interesting point is whether the whole job distribution is random. It could be that the underlying bank has systematically more people with a specific kind of job.

The most important thing to mention here is that single people have nearly the same subscription rate as married ones. This is amazing because on the whole there are two times more people in the data set which are married compared to single ones. This suggests that there is a strong influence of a single person on the subscription rate.

Since the ranking of the variables in terms of counts in the subscription == yes area, corresponds with the overall counts ranking, it is difficult to make a prediction concerning the effect of the education variable. For example in the data set there are the most people with a university degree and the most subscribers were also university graduates.

This chart states that it is most likely to sell the term deposit to a person without a default. Nobody with a default was in the subscriber bin. Ok, there have been only 3 people in the whole data set with a default, but nevertheless it is a reasonable fact.

The housing variable is more or less uniform distributed in the complete data set if one does not take into account the unknwons. Furthermore in this chart there seems no difference in the subscription rate between housing and no housing. So in a predictive model, there would be no effect of this variable. But because of the leck of randomness in the data set. I mean the uniform distribution of the housing variable the effect cannot be measured with this data set, but there is a possibility, that there could be one.

Multivariate Plots Section

The multivariate segments will always cover both, the Plots and Analysis section without making a new header accounting for the Analysis part. My goal is to look now at the integer variables, which will be plotted pairwise against each other. Whereas every time I will use the target variable as color parameter.

If the duration is near or zero, then it does not matter how the Age is distributed, it mostly results in no subscription because the red point are very fat in this area. Further if the duration picks up, a bit, then the subscription rate increases dramatically and is nore or less uniform distributed among the Age variable. If the Duration variable picks up more than a bit, the succesrate rises too, but now it seems that the Age variable spectrum gets thiner. In total one can suggest that the duration variable must be greater than zero in order to achieve subscription=yes.

Most subscription takes place in the low Campaign-Achsis area and it seems a bit uniform distributed among the age variable. So I hold the view that age does not matter if the Campaign Variable is low. Since the Campaign variable stands for the number of contacts performed for each customer in this current Campaign , it is pretty interesting that it is not profitable to contact people very often.

Most subscription takes place when the Passed_Days variable is low, especially the two bars with high density of blue points leads to this opinion. In this areas, the Age variable does not play a role because of the uniform distribution. It is reasonable that the succesrate is high when the Passed_Days variable is relativelly low.

Previous stands for Number of contacts performed before this campaign and for this customer. The density of points is decreasing with the number of contacts in the previous campaign, which means that the succesrate of the current campaign seems not be positively related to the number of contacts in the last campaign.

A relatively low Campaign variable value and a duration greater zero is the zone with the most succesrate. Whereas most non subscribers had a short contact time. Further it seems to be not meaningful whether the Campaign variable is low or high for the non subscribers.

There are two areas where the Passed_Days variable is 3 or 6, where the density of the yes subscribers is highest. The duration at this two lookalike “bars” is between greater zero and 500. In total one can say that Passed_Days and Duration are somehow patternless. I mean that since there is generally highest activity on two days, I hold the view that the relationship one can see is biased a lot.

The lower the value of the Previous Variable, the higher the yes subscription rate. Or the density of the successrate is highest in the most left range but it is not of importance how high the duration is, as long it is between greater zero and 2000. Further, the duration variable is more or less iniform distributed for each Previous Variable value.

The highest density of values is located in the left bottom area, where the Passed_Days variable is between 1 and 9. And the Campaign Variable is relatively low between 0 and 2. Since the blue and red points are distributed with no difference at looking at the graph, one cannot make suggestions when the subscription rate is best if looking at the relationship between the two variables (Campaign and Passed_Days)

The graph is highly left skewed. The most density of points is located when the Previous variable is zero. But the points are mostly red (non subscription), whereas most red points occur when the Campaign variable is greater 9. When the Previous variable takes on values between 0 and 2, the blue points are kind of equally distributed. So one can suggest that there is no impact of the Campaign variable in this area. As recommendation for the business, I conclude that if people habe not been contacted in the previous marketing campaign, which is described by the Previus Variable taking on the value of zero, it makes no sense to contact them now more frequently, thus wasting money, rather one shall take care of the people who have allready been contacted in the previous campaign more often, because of the uniform distributed blue points and the relatively more blue points in the area where the Previous variable is greater zero.

The pattern which first came to my mind when looking at the graph, was the high density of blue points at the day 3 and day 6 mark on the horizontal achsis. Most blue point density occurs at these days when the Previous Variable is zero and two.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot 1

Description 1

The distribution of “Age” is right skewed. 50% of the customers are less than 38 years old and 50% are more than 38. The mean is roughly 40 years. In total there are 41188 people. The peak of the distribution is at 32 years, meaning that most people were that age.

Plot 2

Description 2

The distribution among the days is pretty much uniform. This holds for the yes-subscribers (blue bars) and for the non-subscribers (red bars). Finally, the day of the week has no real impact on the subscription probability because of the uniform distribution among all days.

Plot 3

Description 3

The “Duration” variable stands for the time a customer was contacted. It is shown in seconds from zero to 5000. The “Campaign” variable represents how often a customer was contacted in this marketing campaign. Further the “Subscription” variable can be yes or no. Whereas the target product is sold when the point is colored blue and red otherwise.

The most profitable combination of the 2 variables (Campaign and Duration) is located in the left non zero area for both variables. The highest succesrate is then, if the duration is between non zero and 2000 and when the number of contacts to the customer is between roughly one and five.

Reflection

The enclosed data file contains real customer data from a retail bank, collected from May 2008 to June 2013. The bank had a goal to sell a product. In this case it was a term deposit. The marketing campaigns were based on phone calls. Often, more than one contact to the same customer was required in order to assess if the targeted product is subscribed to by a customer, which is indicated by 'yes' or 'no' to subscribe to a deposit.

At the begining I just focussed on each variable alone, in order to understand the meaning of it, which basically was not very easy in this data set. After doing that, I resumed with the tasks of the project wanted. The next step was to analyze each variable by plotting it and the corresponding counts. So I came to the idea that my goal as a data analyst is to help the compoany to make more money. Thus I realised that the variable of interest is “Subscription”. Only a customer who subscribed, is a good one. So I started the bivariate plots section where I looked at each variable in realtionship to the target variable (Subscription). This was done with the help of so called bar charts in dodge style format. Thus it was possible to see whether there were some pattern, which could help to understand what factors drive the subscription.

In the last step, I took the integer variable of the data set and plotted them against each other in all possible combinations. Further I used the target variable as the color in these plots in order to make patterns visible which maybe not always could be expected.

Concerns about the data set

One thing is not visible in the data set, and that is the worker who made the calls to the potential customers. I hold the view that making such analysis leads sometimes to wrong recommendations. There basically could be one worker who is that kind of skilled to sell the product on the phone, so he could drive the data in one specific direction. Or the otherway round, there are many lazy unskilled workers which are basically weak in selling.

I think there must be definitelly created a new variable which stands for each worker who did the job.
